message: Hello! I found that the 'stove' tool is your best friend for initial value generation; always cook raw proteins and vegetables first (e.g., raw beef -> cooked beef, carrot -> cooked carrot). Combining two cooked proteins (e.g., cooked beef + cooked bacon) or a cooked protein with a cooked vegetable often results in high-value items (40-80 points). However, be careful not to overcomplicate dishes; adding a third or fourth cooked ingredient, especially grains like 'tortilla' or 'wheat' to an already valuable medley (80+ points), frequently causes the value to drop significantly, sometimes to 0 or even negative. Aim for 2-3 well-chosen cooked ingredients in your final dish for optimal scores. Good luck!

message: Hello! To achieve high scores (100) in this game, focus on this pattern: 1. Use the 'stove' tool on all raw ingredients (protein and vegetable will gain value, grain might not initially). 2. Use the 'water' tool on any 'cooked grain' items (like cooked rice, wheat, bread, tortilla) that are still at 0 value, as this usually makes them 'soaked cooked' and increases their value to 20. 3. Combine one 'cooked protein' with one 'cooked vegetable' to get a score of 60. 4. Then, combine this new item with one 'soaked cooked grain' to reach a score of 100. Avoid combining too many items (more than one protein, one vegetable, one grain) or reapplying 'stove' to already complex 'cooked' items, as this can lead to negative values.

Next, use the 'stove' on your raw grain (rice, wheat, corn), then immediately use 'water' on that 'cooked' grain to make it 'soaked cooked' (also worth 20). Finally, combine your 'cooked protein' and 'soaked cooked grain' to get a dish worth 60. To reach 100, add your 'cooked vegetable' to this dish. Do not add a fourth ingredient, as it often drops the value significantly to 0 or even negative. Good luck!
